Specification reference: [[OCR A Chemistry Specification#Determination of formulae|2.1.3 Amount of substance: Determination of formulae]]
- Hydrated salt - ionic solid containing water molecules, e.g. CuSO4
- Anhydrous salt - ionic solid containing no water molecules
- Water of crystallisation - water molecules that form an essential part of the crystalline structure of a compound

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Calculating the formula of a hydrated salt

- If we know the Mr of both the hydrated and anhydrous salt, you can work out the difference to see how many moles of water this represents

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- If the Mr is unknown, an experiment can be carried out to see how much mass is lost when the hydrated salt is heated until all the water is lost. We can then see how many moles of water this represents.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Stoichiometry - the calculation of relative quantities of reactants and products in chemical reactions, based on the law of conservation of matter
- In a balanced chemical equation, the balancing numbers tell us the ratio of moles of each substance taking part in a chemical reaction. This is also known as the stoichiometry of the reaction
- EMMA method: Equation, Moles, Moles, Answer
